{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616628"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:06:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16412"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16412"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9103"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73401"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9103"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58868"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1009"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10378"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21624"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73401"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.aihw.gov.au/reports/dementia/dementia-in-aus/contents/about\u0022\u003EAustralian Institute of Health and Welfare\u003C/a\u003E estimates that 401,300 Australians are living with dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn 2020, dementia was the second leading cause of death in Australia, and the leading cause of death among Australian women.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following combinations represents the three most common causes of dementia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alzheimer disease, Huntington disease, Parkinson disease","Traumatic brain injury, Alzheimer disease, brain malignancy","Parkinson disease, traumatic brain injury, substance-induced dementia","Alzheimer disease, Lewy body disease, vascular disease","Frontotemporal dementia, Lewy body disease, traumatic brain injury"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe three most common causes of dementia are \u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer disease\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Evascular disease\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003ELewy body disease\u003C/strong\u003E, which together account for approximately 80-90% of all dementia cases. Alzheimer disease is the most common, accounting for about 60-70% of cases, followed by vascular dementia (15-20%) and Lewy body dementia (5-10%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuntington disease\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dementia but are much less common causes. Huntington disease is a rare genetic condition, while Parkinson disease dementia typically develops in advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETraumatic brain injury\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrain malignancy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause cognitive impairment but are not among the most common causes of dementia. Traumatic brain injury presents acutely and both these conditions have different neurological symptoms compared to dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstance-induced dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in the differential diagnosis but is not among the top three most common causes. This includes alcohol-related dementia and medication side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrontotemporal dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is an important cause of early-onset dementia but accounts for only about 2-5% of all dementia cases. It typically presents with behavioural changes or language difficulties rather than memory impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that mixed dementia is common, particularly in older adults. The most frequent combination is Alzheimer disease with vascular components. Recognition of the underlying cause(s) helps guide management, including the potential role of preventive strategies for vascular risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alzheimer disease, vascular dementia, and Lewy body dementia account for 80-90% of all dementia cases.","Mixed dementia (particularly Alzheimer disease with vascular components) is common in older adults.","Early recognition of dementia subtype helps guide management and prognosis discussions."],"references":["Gale SA, Acar D, Daffner KR. Dementia. Am J Med. 2018 Oct;131(10):1161-1169. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2018.01.022. Epub 2018 Feb 6. PMID: 29425707.","B\u0142aszczyk JW. Pathogenesis of Dementia. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Dec 29;24(1):543. doi: 10.3390/ijms24010543. PMID: 36613988; PMCID: PMC9820433.","Qiu C, De Ronchi D, Fratiglioni L. The epidemiology of the dementias: an update. Curr Opin Psychiatry. 2007 Jul;20(4):380-5. doi: 10.1097/YCO.0b013e32816ebc7b. PMID: 17551353.","Dintica CS, Yaffe K. Epidemiology and Risk Factors for Dementia. Psychiatr Clin North Am. 2022 Dec;45(4):677-689. doi: 10.1016/j.psc.2022.07.011. Epub 2022 Oct 14. PMID: 36396272."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58868"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16412"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58868"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T16:16:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T09:50:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","